<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-380-128  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 380 128.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Jan 1990 v63 n1 p85(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The buying spree over, decline sets in; with production slowing,Randamp;D picks up for the next chip generation. (1990 outlook for thesemiconductor production equipment industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Runyon, Stan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Semiconductor production equipment industry revenues will declineabout three percent to $3.7 billion in 1990, reflecting a cyclicalpattern that peaked with 50 percent growth in 1988.andP;  Chip vendorspurchased large amounts of semiconductor fabrication equipment inthe last two years for new generations of microprocessors andmemory devices and for production facilities in Europe that wereto be build before the 1992 market unification.andP;  Dataquest Inc(San Jose, CA) believes the next cycle of equipment investmentshould begin in late 1990 for volume production of 4M-bit dynamicrandom-access memories (DRAMs).andP;  The semiconductor productionequipment industry, meanwhile, will retrench and develop equipmentfor forthcoming generations of 16M-bit DRAMs and other advancedintegrated circuits.andP;  Japanese equipment suppliers are expected tosurpass US wafer-fabrication vendors in sales in 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SemiconductorsIndustry AnalysisMarket AnalysisOutlookPreview of Coming YearForecastingRevenueSemiconductor Production Equipment.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Growth in semiconductor production equipment industry revenues:1988-90. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>